<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 27 日星期四 17:17:47 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[ECB Raises Rates, Says Pausing Is an Option]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>总统克里斯蒂娜·拉加德表示：“我们可能加息，也可能维持不变” <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001089186"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823967?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">欧洲央行希望将通胀率降至 2%。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：亚历克斯·克劳斯/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001089186"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/tom-fairless" itemprop="url" rel="author">汤姆·费尔莱斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 27 日中午 12:51（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ecb-rate-decision-july-83e574cd"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>法兰克福——欧洲央行将关键利率提高了四分之一个百分点，但暗示可能很快会暂停长达一年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ecb-rate-decision-june-532e7e87?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的加息行动</a>，导致欧元暴跌。</p><p>欧洲央行连续第九次加息，使得该行的存款利率从一年前的零以下升至 22 年来的高点 3.75%。尽管<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">欧元区利率仍明显低于美联储 5.25% 至 5.5% 的基准利率，但与前一天美联储加息 25 个基点相</a>呼应。</p><p>欧洲央行的信号凸显了其与美联储相比面临的困境。欧元区的通货膨胀率高于美国，而经济增长则要弱得多，这在一定程度上反映了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-war-becomes-grinding-fight-medics-battle-to-save-soldiers-in-ukraine-b04a976a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">俄罗斯在邻国乌克兰发动战争</a>的冲击。欧洲央行需要在通胀持续太长时间过高的风险与迫在眉睫的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-u-s-drug-companies-could-tip-europe-into-recession-aa6f34cf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">经济衰退威胁</a>之间取得平衡，经济衰退已困扰该集团数月。</p><p>欧元兑美元汇率下跌逾美分，至略低于1.10美元，欧元区政府债务收益率下跌，因为投资者认为欧洲央行将对进一步加息持谨慎态度。数据显示上季度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-gdp-report-economic-growth-92482437?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国经济增长</a>快于预期，美元兑外币汇率上涨，加剧了欧元的下滑。</p><p>欧洲央行行长拉加德在新闻发布会上承认，欧元区经济前景已经恶化，特别是制造业。</p><p> “对于 9 月份和随后的会议将做出哪些决定，我们持开放态度……我们可能会加息，也可能会按兵不动。 9月份的决定还不是确定的，每次会议的结果可能会有所不同，”拉加德表示。她表示，未来的利率决定将基于即将公布的经济数据。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824794?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">欧洲央行行长克里斯蒂娜·拉加德表示，利率决定将在每次会议上做出。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：凯·普芬巴赫/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这种模糊性反映了欧洲央行行长面临的高度不确定性，因为增长前景黯淡，不同地区的通胀下降速度不同，过去的加息对家庭和企业支出的影响存在滞后性。</p><p>世界各地的央行都发出信号，经过一年多的大幅加息，利率已接近峰值。但他们对宣布战胜通货膨胀持谨慎态度，过去两年事实证明，通货膨胀是一个比预期更顽固的敌人。</p><p>澳大利亚、加拿大和美国的央行最近暂停加息数周或数月，然后又开始加息。继上个月短暂暂停加息之后，美联储周三将基准利率上调至 5.25% 至 5.5% 之间，美联储主席杰罗姆·鲍威尔 (Jerome Powell)</p>表示现在判断此次加息是否会结束美联储的一系列加息还为时过早。预计英国央行下周将把利率从目前的 5% 上调至少 25 个基点。<p></p><p>尽管美国经济强劲增长，但欧元区自去年年底以来一直陷入停滞。商业调查显示未来将面临更多痛苦， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/germany-is-dragging-down-europes-economy-bd44ffa3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">特别是在欧元区</a>最大经济体德国。银行贷款急剧恶化， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-07-25-2023/card/eurozone-corporate-loan-demand-hits-record-low-ecb-survey-suggests-lGlac1ogcHIbRinGYpvo?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">商业贷款需求</a>降至历史低点。</p><p>欧洲经济逆风应有助于抑制通胀，欧元区 6 月份通胀率降至 5.5%，为近 18 个月来的最低水平，但仍远高于欧洲央行 2% 的目标。欧洲央行的加息也应该会对企业和家庭支出产生滞后影响​​。</p><p>另一方面，欧洲就业市场强劲，工资快速上涨。欧元区的核心通胀（不包括食品和能源）被认为是衡量通胀走向的更好指标，近一年来一直徘徊在 5% 左右。欧元持续疲软可能会导致进口产品更加昂贵，从而引发通货膨胀。所有这些都意味着，目前尚不清楚欧洲央行的举措是否有助于将通胀率延迟至 2%，或者物价压力是否可能保持在高位。</p><p> “美联储不需要在 9 月份再次加息。他们已经进入了限制性区域。判断欧洲的情况比较困难，因为通货膨胀仍然相当严重，”道富环球投资顾问公司的高级投资策略师德斯·劳伦斯表示。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>欧洲央行是否正在采取正确的措施来应对通货膨胀？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Refinitiv 的数据显示，投资者预计欧洲央行将在今年晚些时候将利率提高至 4%，然后在明年晚些时候开始降息。欧洲央行官员表示，借贷成本可能会在一段时间内保持高位，未来几个月的新数据对于确定利率需要上升多少至关重要。</p><p>拉加德在解释美国和欧元区利率差距时表示，大西洋两岸的通胀“是两种不同的野兽”，美国的通胀更多地受到强劲需求的推动。她补充说，与欧洲央行不同，美联储一开始的利率并不是低于零。</p><p>本周早些时候，国际货币基金组织官员敦促欧洲央行考虑将利率提高到3.75%以上，以防止高通胀根深蒂固。国际货币基金组织欧洲部主任阿尔弗雷德·卡默（Alfred Kammer）和他的同事路易斯·布兰道-马克斯（Luis Brandao-Marques）在博客文章中写道：“我们认为（欧元区）通胀在 2025 年中期之前不会回到目标。”官员们警告说，粘性通胀最终将迫使欧洲央行提高利率，并在更长时间内将其恢复到目标水平，从而导致随后更严重的经济衰退。</p><p>周四被问及欧洲央行是否还有更多需要解决的问题时，拉加德表示：“目前我不会这么说。”</p><p>摩根大通资产管理公司全球利率投资组合经理贾森·戴维斯表示：“我们相信现在已接近加息周期的结束。” “我们预计欧洲央行将在一段时间内保持按兵不动，只有在劳动力市场开始疲软且核心通胀明显回归目标时才会降息。”</p><p>写信给 Tom Fairless，邮箱为<a href="mailto:tom.fairless@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">tom.fairless@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 16:51:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ecb-rate-decision-july-83e574cd</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ecb-rate-decision-july-83e574cd<author><![CDATA[Tom Fairless]]></author><category>银行/信贷</category><category>金融服务</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>欧元区数据/政策</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>克里斯蒂娜·拉加德</category><category>杰罗姆·鲍威尔</category><category>德斯·劳伦斯</category><category>阿尔弗雷德·卡默</category><category>路易斯·布兰当-马克斯</category><category>贾森·戴维斯</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>欧元区数据</category><category>政策</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>银行业</category><category>信用</category><category>金融服务</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Missile Strikes on Odesa Are Destroying Its Russian Legacy]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>对乌克兰城市大教堂和历史中心的袭击使更多居民对莫斯科产生了反感<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824774/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="敖德萨的主显圣容大教堂在俄罗斯对乌克兰港口城市的袭击中遭受严重破坏。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>乌克兰港口城市敖德萨的主显圣容大教堂在俄罗斯袭击中遭受严重破坏。 Nina Liashonok/Ukrinform/Zuma Press <span>Nina Liashonok/Ukrinform/Zuma Press</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001089594"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001089594"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/matthew-luxmoore" itemprop="url" rel="author">马修·卢克斯摩尔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 27 日上午 10:06 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/catherine-the-great-founded-odesa-now-missiles-are-destroying-its-russian-legacy-73f98c7c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>乌克兰敖德萨——导弹将敖德萨高耸的主显圣容大教堂的整个侧翼夷为平地。曾经俯瞰祭坛的巨大圆顶的柱子现在倾斜地矗立着，随时可能倒塌。基督教圣徒的壁画被烧焦得面目全非。</p><p>对于敖德萨主要东正教教堂的神职人员来说，上周<a href="https://www.wsj.com/video/russian-strikes-on-odesa-destroy-historic-cathedral/55D50901-F1BE-4EAE-BF4C-08C0D9F2838A.html?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">坠入其金色圆顶的</a>俄罗斯火箭象征着俄罗斯正在这座传奇港口城市摧毁自己的历史遗产。</p><p> “他们向自己开枪，”叶文·古蒂亚尔神父一边走在维修和清理人员中间，一边检查受损情况，说道。 “这座大教堂是俄罗斯在这座城市存在的象征。现在，祝福这座教堂的那个国家正在摧毁它。”</p><p>自从莫斯科本月宣布<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-says-it-is-pulling-out-of-ukraine-grain-deal-68190d1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">退出</a>一项允许乌克兰恢复谷物出口的国际协议以来，敖德萨一直成为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-strikes-odesa-port-after-quitting-black-sea-grain-deal-4df967bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">俄罗斯轰炸行动</a>的目标，而谷物出口是世界大部分地区的重要生命线。</p><p>过去10天连续几个晚上，它都遭到自杀式无人机和火箭的攻击，其中包括该市防空系统没有能力拦截的海射导弹。</p><p>乌克兰官员表示，最近的袭击故意针对该港口，破坏了关键基础设施，并于周四杀死了那里的一名保安。该港口现在闲置，使乌克兰本已陷入困境的战时经济陷入困境，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-russia-killed-the-ukraine-grain-deal-faf1f8c5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">导致数百万吨食品腐烂</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824777?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一名牧师在敖德萨主显圣容大教堂的废墟中行走。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Oleksandr Gimanov/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824781?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">基辅表示，尽管俄罗斯否认，但大教堂遭到的破坏显然是导弹袭击造成的。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Oleksandr Gimanov/法新社/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>但轰炸也袭击了这座历史悠久的市中心，摧毁了俄罗斯认为是其历史上值得骄傲的一部分的建筑。敖德萨由俄罗斯女皇叶卡捷琳娜大帝于 18 世纪建立，长期以来一直被视为帝国的瑰宝，也是来到黑海港口进行贸易的各民族的熔炉。现在，它因俄罗斯护卫舰和军事基地发射的火箭而伤痕累累。</p><p> “我想让全世界听到：人们，睁开眼睛——那些仍然同情俄罗斯的人，你们疯了吗？”敖德萨市市长亨纳迪·特鲁哈诺夫在接受采访时表示。 “晚上来敖德萨参观防空洞，看看睡在那里的儿童和老人的眼睛。”</p><p>敖德萨的历史中心一月份被联合国教科文组织列为世界遗产，联合国机构表示，此举是为了确保这座城市免遭进一步破坏。俄罗斯当时谴责将敖德萨列入名单的决定，称对其遗产的唯一威胁来自“乌克兰的民族主义政权”。</p><p>周日，在一次大规模导弹袭击中，一枚火箭撞击市政厅附近的一个住宅区，产生的冲击波对几座 19 世纪的建筑造成严重损坏，其中包括科学家之家，这是一个举办音乐会和聚会的场所，当时正在准备一场博物馆展览，庆祝其成立周年。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1088" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/d44799e8-7f86-4fa1-ac1a-bbf5577d21d2-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>本周，自 2005 年起担任该中心主任的斯维特兰娜·热科娃 (Svitlana Zhekova) 走过其破烂不堪的房间时，几乎热泪盈眶。 “这座建筑是我的一部分，”她说。工人们正在清理花园里的碎片，街上附近房屋的居民正在更换窗户，清理庭院里的弹片和碎玻璃。</p><p>市长特鲁哈诺夫表示，该市仍在评估历史中心的受损程度，并将与联合国教科文组织合作制定修复计划。他说，俄罗斯的袭击是为了在民众中制造恐慌，迫使基辅与俄罗斯进行谈判。他说，相反，这座城市仍然目中无人，他的政府正集中精力增加居民可用的防空洞数量。</p><p>特鲁哈诺夫过去因发表各种被视为亲俄罗斯的言论而受到批评，但自战争开始以来，他经常谴责俄罗斯的入侵。他批准拆除市中心的凯瑟琳大帝雕像，并表示他正在监督一项更改全市俄罗斯街道名称的运动。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>敖德萨的未来会怎样？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>他说，针对大教堂的袭击使得俄语城市敖德萨的更多居民开始反对莫斯科。这一转变<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-orthodox-church-holiest-site-russian-invasion-efdba553?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">尤其具有象征意义</a>，因为直到去年，该教堂还隶属于俄罗斯东正教，其领导人</p>基里尔宗主教支持俄罗斯入侵乌克兰，并祝福前往前线的俄罗斯军队。<p></p><p>大教堂被无神论的苏联当局摧毁后，经过一年的修复工作，基里尔于 2010 年亲自为这座大教堂举行了祝圣仪式。现在，敖德萨教区的神父古蒂亚尔和其他神职人员表示，基里尔已经背叛了教会，不再指望莫斯科。</p><p>敖德萨教区84岁的主教阿加凡格尔在大教堂被击中的第二天，站在大教堂的正门旁哭泣了几分钟，难以想象当时的场景。</p><p> “我们重建了这座教堂，它成为了城市的中心，”他在本周访问期间说道。 “现在，一枚俄罗斯火箭摧毁了我们共同努力创造的一切，将其变成了死亡和仇恨的象征。”</p><p>俄罗斯东正教尚未对损坏大教堂的袭击发表评论。俄罗斯国防部在没有证据的情况下表示，它的目标是正在准备对俄罗斯发动袭击的地方，并指责乌克兰的防空系统。基辅表示，损坏程度显然是导弹袭击造成的，而不是被击落的火箭造成的。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="842" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824782?width=1260&amp;height=842" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">敖德萨历史中心被指定为联合国教科文组织世界遗产几个月后，就发生了罢工。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Hector Adolfo Quintanar Perez/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824791?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">上个月，俄罗斯导弹袭击摧毁了敖德萨的一个仓库。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：oleksandr gimanov/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>大教堂入口处的一小部分现已被分配用于继续提供服务。最近的一个下午，神父凯里洛·马科格纽克（Kyrylo Makogonyuk）在面对毁灭场景时读了经文。</p><p>他面前的一个看台上有一座敖德萨女赞助人的圣像，它是从废墟中被救出来的。本周，一阵强风吹过这座城市，穿过教堂被毁坏的东翼的一个大洞，吹乱了牧师弥撒书的书页。当大教堂天花板的一块塌下来时，他几乎没有退缩。</p><p>自敖德萨港口关闭以来一直失业的商船船长奥列克西·马里舍夫周三参加了教堂的仪式。</p><p>马里舍夫出生在俄罗斯，战前他的员工有一半是俄罗斯人。尽管克里米亚是俄罗斯于 2014 年从乌克兰吞并的黑海半岛，但他们仍会与乌克兰人一起喝酒。</p><p>他说，现在他再也不会同意与俄罗斯人合作。</p><p> “这座教堂是他们建城的记忆，”他说。 “现在他们已经摧毁了那段记忆。”</p><p>写信给马修·卢克斯摩尔： <a href="mailto:matthew.luxmoore@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">matthew.luxmoore@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824793?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">敖德萨居民清扫受损大教堂外的碎玻璃。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：oleksandr gimanov/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 14:06:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/catherine-the-great-founded-odesa-now-missiles-are-destroying-its- Russian-legacy-73f98c7c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/catherine-the-great-founded-odesa-now-missiles-are-destroying-its- Russian-legacy-73f98c7c<author><![CDATA[Matthew Luxmoore]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>宗教</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>宗教</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Biden’s New Border Rules Don’t Deter Venezuelans]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>非法过境减少，但委内瑞拉难民仍在寻求入境<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824234/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="拜登政府援助古巴、尼加拉瓜和委内瑞拉移民的计划对委内瑞拉人来说效果不佳。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>拜登政府援助古巴、尼加拉瓜和委内瑞拉移民的计划对委内瑞拉人来说效果不佳。路易斯·安东尼奥·罗哈斯 (Luis Antonio Rojas) 供职于《华尔街日报》<span>路易斯·安东尼奥·罗哈斯 (Luis Antonio Rojas) 供职于《华尔街日报》</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087994"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087994"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/michelle-hackman" itemprop="url" rel="author">米歇尔·哈克曼 (Michelle Hackman)</a></span>在华盛顿、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/juan-forero" itemprop="url" rel="author">胡安·福雷罗 (Juan Forero)</a></span>在<span class="author" itemprop="name">哥伦比亚</span>拉斯特卡斯、圣地亚哥·佩雷斯 ( <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/santiago-perez" itemprop="url" rel="author">Santiago Pérez</a></span> ) 和<span class="author" itemprop="name">墨西哥塔帕丘拉</span>(Tapachula)</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 27 日上午 10:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidens-new-border-rules-dont-deter-desperate-venezuelans-9a3c022b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>拜登政府的新边境执法措施减少了非法越境，但拉丁美洲各地数百万委内瑞拉难民（其中许多人向北迁移）仍然对美国构成挑战</p><p>超过 730 万委内瑞拉人离开了自己的国家，成为最大的难民群体，领先于逃离饱受战争蹂躏家园的乌克兰人和叙利亚人。</p><p>移民政策研究所最近的一份报告显示，约有<a href="https://reliefweb.int/report/colombia/betting-legality-latin-american-and-caribbean-responses-venezuelan-displacement-crisis" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">640 万人在拉丁美洲定居</a>。许多人现在正在迁移，逃离委内瑞拉的经济危机或他们所前往的国家，因为缺乏就业机会而灰心丧气，在某些情况下还面临敌意。政府数据显示，委内瑞拉人比任何其他国家的人都更多地通过中美洲向北流动，许多人试图跨越美墨边境，尽管后果更为严重。</p><p>巴拿马当局称，徒步穿越巴拿马达连峡（Darien Gap）的委内瑞拉移民人数预计今年将达到 20 万人，比 2022 年增加 5 万人。达连峡是委内瑞拉人前往美国的重要走廊。这将是巴拿马移民当局预计今年来自各国的 40 万人中的一半。去年，包括委内瑞拉人在内，总人数为 284,000 人。</p><p> “我们正在逃离我们的国家，为了寻找生计，”41 岁的委内瑞拉人尤西比奥·卡斯蒂略 (Eusebio Castillo) 最近在达里恩峡谷边缘说道。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=573D0B7D-E22C-42C8-B81C-0750968A109D&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fbidens-new-border-rules-dont-deter-desperate-venezuelans-9a3c022b&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">第 42 条允许美国当局以公共卫生为由迅速驱逐移民，该条已于 5 月到期。 《华尔街日报》解释了该政策是什么、其对边境的影响以及接下来会发生什么。照片：约翰摩尔/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>前往美国的卡斯蒂略表示，在放弃之前，他已经尝试前往厄瓜多尔和哥伦比亚。他说，没有工作文件，他几乎无法维持收支平衡。</p><p> “你甚至无法日复一日地生活。你生活在一场灾难中，”前陆军中士卡斯蒂略说。 “我想要稳定的工作，有尊严的工作。”</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-the-new-immigration-system-works-after-title-42-ends-2fba7498" target="_blank" class="icon none">拜登政府的边境措施</a>——旨在引导移民远离边境，转而支持几种新创建的进入美国的合法选择的一系列胡萝卜加大棒——总体上达到了预期的效果。自 5 月 11 日（即<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-is-title-42-border-rules-migration-11649118539" target="_blank" class="icon none">第 42 条）大流行时期措施到期</a>以来， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/border-arrests-have-dropped-70-since-title-42-ended-biden-administration-says-3d00dc48" target="_blank" class="icon none">非法过境活动</a>有所减少。</p><p>但政府在一月份专门针对来自古巴、尼加拉瓜和委内瑞拉这三个独裁国家的移民推出的一项计划，对委内瑞拉人来说并不像对其他两个国家那样有效。</p><p>根据该计划，只要找到私人担保人，潜在移民就可以申请两年期工作许可证移居美国，事实证明，这条道路比试图非法越境更具吸引力。尽管委内瑞拉人利用了该计划，但自该计划启动以来，仍有 78,000 人试图非法越境，相比之下，只有不到 10,000 名古巴人和大约 5,000 名尼加拉瓜人。</p><p>委内瑞拉移民表示，试图非法入境<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/venezuelans-flee-again-this-time-to-the-u-s-11650039323?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">反映了他们的绝望</a>。移民官员指出，许多委内瑞拉人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/backlash-against-venezuelan-refugees-grows-across-south-america-1535132655" target="_blank" class="icon none">仍在逃离自己的国家</a>，那里的大多数人都面临着贫困，而且 2022 年经济的小幅改善也只是昙花一现。事实上的美元化经济使贫穷的委内瑞拉人难以维持收支平衡。大多数赚取当地货币的委内瑞拉人都在与通货膨胀作斗争，经济学家称通货膨胀率高达 400%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824248?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">墨西哥已停止拘留来自委内瑞拉等国、进入该国南部与危地马拉边境的前往美国的移民。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的路易斯·安东尼奥·罗哈斯</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>其他人长期以来一直认为他们的流离失所是暂时的，但现在打消了回家的想法。</p><p>安德鲁·塞利说：“现在，许多委内瑞拉人意识到他们可能永远流离失所，有些人正在寻找机会，也许未来的生活会更轻松一些。”</p>华盛顿特区无党派智库移民政策研究所所长，也是该研究所最近报告的合著者。<p></p><p>塞利说，随着人们对回国失去希望，前往美国是一个更有吸引力的选择。华盛顿的美洲对话称，就业机会更加充足，利润也更加丰厚，使得人们可以向委内瑞拉的亲戚寄钱，那里有三分之一的家庭依靠汇款生存。两国政府之间的关系冻结意味着那些没有资格在美国获得庇护的委内瑞拉人不能轻易被驱逐回自己的祖国。塞利说，在美国取得成功的委内瑞拉人越多，他们向其他希望尝试的人传达的信息就越多。</p><p>今年 5 月，18 岁的梅兰尼·梅莱西奥 (Melany Melesio) 与来自委内瑞拉中部马拉凯家乡的一群邻居一起，艰难地穿过达里恩峡谷 (Darien Gap)。</p><p>怀孕五个月后，她靠做小贩赚的 20 美元艰难度日，她离开了自己的国家，因为她说她想让孩子在美国长大</p><p>“我希望他能过上更好的生活，接受更好的教育，”她说。 “我想给他我从未拥有过的一切。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824258?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">巴拿马的达连峡是前往美国的委内瑞拉人的重要走廊。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的塔琳娜·罗德里格斯</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>总部位于委内瑞拉的人权组织 Proiuris 表示，预计今年将有超过 30 万委内瑞拉人离开家园。<br><br>哥伦比亚外交部副部长弗朗西斯科·科伊表示，“流亡潮仍然没有结束”。拉丁美洲约 45% 的流亡委内瑞拉人居住在哥伦比亚。</p><p>中美洲上下以及墨西哥都能感受到来自委内瑞拉的压力。这对墨西哥当局来说尤其具有挑战性，因为许多委内瑞拉人暂时居住在墨西哥，同时在边境等待庇护预约或通过其他途径进入美国</p><p>最近高等法院的一项裁决禁止墨西哥官员将非法越境墨西哥的移民拘留超过 36 小时。而且，与美国一样，墨西哥无法驱逐大多数委内瑞拉人，因为他们的本国政府不会接受驱逐航班。</p><p>被美国驱逐出境的委内瑞拉人被乘飞机或公共汽车送往墨西哥南部，这是一项威慑措施，旨在防止他们集中在美墨边境沿线的社区。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>委内瑞拉难民危机该如何解决？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> 3月中旬，墨西哥停止对来自委内瑞拉等国前往美国的移民进入该国与危地马拉的南部边境进行拘留，并开始用巴士将新移民送往该国其他地区。这样做的目的是防止塔帕丘拉等边境社区出现聚集现象，那里的家庭聚集在桥下，露宿在垃圾堆中。</p><p>据移民援助组织和政府官员称，自美国 5 月结束大流行时期的移民政策 Title 42 以来，每天有超过 4,000 名移民从危地马拉越境进入墨西哥南部。这个数字包括约 1,600 名委内瑞拉人。</p><p> “我们目前正在努力在我们共同的边境上实现更加有序的移民，”墨西哥外交部北美事务首席官罗伯托·贝拉斯科(Roberto Velasco)说。但他补充说，从长远来看，改善委内瑞拉的生活条件至关重要，因为现状是不可持续的。</p><p>委内瑞拉年轻人诺尔伯特·科伊最近一天一路到达墨西哥与德克萨斯州的边境。与他的许多同胞一样，他的计划是越境申请庇护预约。</p><p> “这段旅程并不容易，”科伊说。他说，他的家人和其他十几名来自该国西部苏利亚州的委内瑞拉人一起向北旅行。 “即使我没能成功，至少我尝试过。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——哥伦比亚波哥大的 Kejal Vyas 对本文做出了贡献。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824249?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美国新的边境执法措施减少了非法越境，但拉丁美洲数百万委内瑞拉难民仍然构成挑战。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的路易斯·安东尼奥·罗哈斯</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给 Michelle Hackman（ <a href="mailto:michelle.hackman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">michelle.hackman@wsj.com）</a> 、Juan Forero（ <a href="mailto:juan.forero@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">juan.forero@wsj.com</a> ）和 Santiago Pérez（ <a href="mailto:santiago.perez@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">santiago.perez@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidens-new-border-rules-dont-deter-desperate-venezuelans-9a3c022b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidens-new-border-rules-dont-deter-desperate-venezuelans-9a3c022b<author><![CDATA[Michelle HackmanJuan ForeroSantiago Pérez]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>非法移民</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>非法移民</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S. Economic Growth Accelerates]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>上季度经济增长2.4%，表明美国正在摆脱衰退<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087898"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="581" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824191?width=860&amp;height=581" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">消费者支出一直在推动美国经济。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087898"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sarah-chaney-cambon" itemprop="url" rel="author">莎拉·钱尼·坎本</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 27 日上午 8:49（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-gdp-economy-consumer-spending-92482437"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>尽管美联储<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">提高了利率，</a>美国经济上个季度依然强劲增长，并且远离衰退。</p><p>美国商务部周四表示，第二季度<a href="https://www.bea.gov/data/gdp/gross-domestic-product" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">国内生产总值(GDP)</a>季节性和通胀调整后年增长率为2.4%，略高于今年前三个月2%的增长率。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-economy-retail-sales-may-2023-c9ddefcb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">今年春季消费者支出有所增长</a>，但商品和服务支出增速均放缓。 4 月至 6 月，商业投资有所加强，企业在建筑和设备上的支出强劲。</p><p>总体而言，GDP 报告进一步证明经济在利率上升的情况下仍保持弹性。劳动力市场依然紧张，通胀正在缓解。</p><p>在许多人预计<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/economists-are-cutting-back-their-recession-expectations-74118938?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">经济衰退将在今年年中开始以应对美联储政策后，经济学家现在正在下调经济</a>衰退预期。美联储周三采取行动，将基准利率提高至 22 年来的高点。主席杰罗姆·鲍威尔不排除再次加息的可能性，但强调加息可能需要一段时间才能冷却通胀。</p><p> AC Cutts &amp; Associates 首席经济学家艾米·克鲁斯·卡茨 (Amy Crews Cutts) 在数据发布前表示：“我们已经扭转了这里的风险，不再过度关注衰退，而是在衰退与非衰退之间保持平衡。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="850" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824776?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><h3>消费者支出推动经济发展</h3><p>消费者正在增加在旅行和大件商品等体验方面的支出。美国人正受益于强劲的劳动力市场，工资涨幅最近<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pay-raises-are-finally-beating-inflation-after-two-years-of-falling-behind-3e89bc2d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">超过了降温的通胀。</a></p><p>今年年初，随着供应链中断的缓解，消费者在回流经销商停车场时抢购车辆。他们还在网上和餐馆消费更多。</p><p>尚不清楚今年晚些时候消费者是否会以同样的速度消费。高利率将持续存在，使得美国人经常贷款购买的汽车、电器和其他产品变得更加昂贵。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/student-loan-debt-repayment-money-budget-7d81f540?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">学生贷款偿还</a>将于今年晚些时候恢复。美国人正在耗尽他们在疫情爆发初期在家积累的积蓄。</p><p>德意志银行证券公司高级美国经济学家布雷特·瑞安表示：“有很多煤矿里的金丝雀迹象表明消费者支出将会放缓。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=6B575582-5695-4577-8048-E886C31EFE0B&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fus-gdp-report-economic-growth-92482437&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">美联储主席杰罗姆·鲍威尔周三表示，央行将把基准利率提高四分之一个百分点，使美国利率升至22年来的最高点。照片：内森·霍华德/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>投资数据显示利率的影响</h3><p>公司在年初放缓了投资，削减了设备采购。</p><p>住宅投资下降。商业和住宅投资对利率都高度敏感。</p><p>一些长期力量也在塑造投资趋势。例如，联邦政府在芯片制造厂和电动汽车工厂方面的支出激增，抵消了一些私营部门的削减开支。</p><p>尽管抵押贷款利率上升，但二手房的长期短缺正在帮助支持新建筑。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/housings-recession-already-happened-26bbb505?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">房地产市场低迷</a>最严重的时期可能已经成为过去。随着更多的建设正在进行，未来几个月住宅投资可能会增长。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1300" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824784?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><h3>前景更加乐观</h3><p>消费者、企业和经济学家对前景感到更加乐观。随着<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-june-inflation-ede7f4b1" target="_blank" class="icon none">通胀从历史高位回落</a>且劳动力市场依然吃紧， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-inflation-goes-down-soft-landing-odds-improve-5166e6af" target="_blank" class="icon none">软着陆</a>的前景——即通胀在不出现衰退的情况下回归到接近<a href="https://www.wsj.com/video/series/news-explainers/the-feds-2-inflation-target-explained/F0A8BD11-B153-4E7E-8454-B5C1C8CD12BD?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美联储 2% 的目标</a>——的可能性似乎更大。</p><p>世界大型企业联合会本周表示，7 月份美国消费者信心继续改善，许多美国人对未来表示更加乐观。消费者对经济衰退的担忧减少。</p><p>小企业对经济的悲观情绪有所缓解。商业辅导和同行咨询公司伟事达 (Vistage Worldwide) 的数据显示，7 月，37% 的小企业表示，他们认为未来 12 个月经济将恶化，这是自 2022 年 2 月以来的最佳记录。</p><p>国际货币基金组织周二表示，今年美国和全球的经济增长可能会强于此前的估计。前景的改善反映了劳动力市场的强劲、旅游业等服务业支出的强劲以及金融稳定风险的降低。</p><p>写信给 Sarah Chaney Cambon，邮箱为<a href="mailto:sarah.chaney@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sarah.chaney@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/newsroom-feedback/b53b02aa-8e94-4e61-9c59-71310c5dc08d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 12:49:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-gdp-report-economic-growth-92482437</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-gdp-report-economic-growth-92482437<author><![CDATA[Sarah Chaney Cambon]]></author><category>通货膨胀</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>银行业</category><category>中央银行业务</category><category>银行/信贷</category><category>金融服务</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济增长/衰退</category><category>货币政策</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>个人财务</category><category>消费者支出/预算</category><category>通货膨胀</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济增长</category><category>经济衰退</category><category>货币政策</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>个人财务</category><category>消费支出</category><category>预算编制</category><category>银行业</category><category>中央银行</category><category>信用</category><category>金融服务</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Israeli Protesters Pledge to Intensify Civil Unrest]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>计划于周四举行大规模示威，运动领导人表示他们正在从“遏制转向进攻” <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001089294"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824744?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周一，抗议者封锁了耶路撒冷以色列议会大楼外的一条道路。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Kobi Wolf/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001089294"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">多夫·利伯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 27 日上午 7:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-protesters-pledge-to-intensify-civil-unrest-76b69af9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>特拉维夫——以色列抗议领导人周四宣布在特拉维夫举行大规模示威，这是针对总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">司法改革</a>而增加骚乱的新计划的一部分。</p><p>这次抗议活动发生在犹太日历上最阴沉的斋戒日之一——Tisha B&#39;Av，纪念耶路撒冷第一座和第二座古庙被毁，以及历史上其他伟大的犹太悲剧。抗议组织者利用禁食的时机，称内塔尼亚胡正在造成犹太家园的第三次破坏。</p><p>以色列物理学家、抗议运动领导人之一希克马·布雷斯勒 (Shikma Bressler) 表示：“一切合法和非暴力的事情都可以讨论。”布雷斯勒表示，这可能意味着更多的罢工以及主要高速公路和公共交通的中断。</p><p>周一，以色列议会<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">通过了一项更广泛计划的第一部分</a>，以限制最高法院的权力并将更多控制权交给立法者。</p><p>该计划的支持者表示，法院由自由派法官控制，他们太快地推翻了人民的意愿，必须加以控制，以恢复政府各部门之间的适当平衡。反对者表示，此举旨在削弱法院，以便内塔尼亚胡的右翼、极端民族主义和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-ultra-orthodox-haredim-military-service-supreme-court-of-ultra-orthodox-jews-shakes-israels-sense-of-identity-b3155e01?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">宗教保守派政党</a>联盟能够颁布立法，摧毁以色列的自由民主制度，并通过立法，践踏少数群体的权利，并将更多的宗教信仰强加于公众。领域。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisraeli-protesters-pledge-to-intensify-civil-unrest-76b69af9&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">以色列医生周二举行罢工，当局在因总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府进行的司法改革而发生骚乱的夜晚，强行将抗议者从道路上带走。照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>内塔尼亚胡和他的盟友表示，他们正在执行选民的意愿。一些联盟成员将一些抗议者视为无政府主义者。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡周一在向全国发表讲话时表示，“执行选民的意愿绝不是‘民主的终结’”。 “这是民主的本质。”</p><p>议会于 7 月 30 日开始夏季休会，直到 10 月中旬才会返回。内塔尼亚胡表示，他将在秋季继续推进改革，但在春季和夏季谈判失败后将寻求与反对派妥协。</p><p> “反对派不会参与一场空洞的谈判，”以色列反对派领导人亚伊尔·拉皮德周一晚间表示。</p><p>周一，该法律通过之前和之后都发生了大规模示威活动，并持续到深夜。在投票前，抗议者试图阻止进入耶路撒冷议会。 After the vote passed, protesters blocked highways across the country and clashed with police.</p><p> But by Tuesday, things had mostly quieted down and it was unclear where the protest movement would go next. Some leaders say they are still plotting how to fully unleash and sustain the movement.</p><p> Wednesday night, the Kaplan Force, one of the main protest groups, announced that the movement was moving from one of “containment to offense” and called Netanyahu&#39;s government “illegitimate.” The group is named after Kaplan Street in Tel Aviv, where mass demonstrations against the judicial plan have taken place for 29 weeks straight.</p><p> Right-wing groups supporting the judicial legislation have also come out in large numbers at times, although there have been no large demonstrations in favor of the overhaul since the legislation passed. Many supporters of the plan say they feel vindicated by the law&#39;s passage.</p><p> The protest movement has brought as many as half a million people to Israel&#39;s streets at times, according to organizers, in a county of 9.3 million people. It is being led by military reservists, former security officials, business and technology industry leaders, public intellectuals and youth organizing through WhatsApp. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824745?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An Israeli military reservist signs a pledge to suspend voluntary service in response to passage of the judicial overhaul.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿米尔·科恩/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>A full picture of the threat from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">thousands of military reservists</a> to refuse to report for duty if the legislation passed remains unclear. On Tuesday, Israeli military spokesman Daniel Hagari said there had been a rise in requests by reservists to cease their service. While no damage had yet been done to the military&#39;s operational capabilities, he said it could happen if the trend continues.</p><p> Netanyahu has said that refusing to serve is an illegitimate form of protest.</p><p> Ron Scherf, one of the leaders of Brothers in Arms, a group representing military reservists, said they are going to focus demonstrations on Netanyahu and Defense Minister Yoav Gallant, who they see as primarily responsible for harming the unity of the military.</p><p> “In any country in which there is a dictator, a people&#39;s army won&#39;t work,” he said.</p><p> Bressler said that the first seven months of protests had awakened a liberal democratic camp in Israel that was “unaware of its size and strength.” Now, she said, she is thinking about how to use the potential of this camp. She also noted that over the past week, there had been a large increase in the number of young protesters joining demonstrations, infusing them with a higher intensity and leading to clashes with police.</p><p>写信给 Dov Lieber，邮箱为<a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-protesters-pledge-to-intensify-civil-unrest-76b69af9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-protesters-pledge-to-intensify-civil-unrest-76b69af9<author><![CDATA[Dov Lieber]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>本杰明·内塔尼亚胡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[An Unwelcome Visitor Returns This Summer. Hint: It’s Covid.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Hearing about a smattering of Covid cases again? There&#39;s a reason <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824544/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Margeaux Walter for The Wall Street Journal <span>Margeaux Walter for The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087824"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087824"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sumathi-reddy" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sumathi Reddy</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 27, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/covid-19-rates-rising-summer-780ab1d7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Summer is bringing us hot days, vacations—and a Covid bump.</p><p> If you are surprised to learn that your neighbor, co-worker or kid&#39;s best friend just tested positive for Covid-19, don&#39;t be. Measures of Covid rates including virus levels in wastewater, ER visits, test positivity and hospital admissions are increasing nationally, according to the most recent Centers for Disease Control and Prevention <a href="https://covid.cdc.gov/covid-data-tracker/?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email#maps_new-admissions-rate-county" target="_blank" class="icon none">data</a> . The good news is that we are starting from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-covid-19-deaths-and-hospitalizations-near-new-lows-9151bc18?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">very low rates</a> .</p><p> Doctors are watching the current trends for clues to Covid&#39;s yearly pattern going forward. Other <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-does-flu-spread-compared-with-covid-what-to-know-as-flu-cases-surge-11667882271?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">respiratory viruses such as flu</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fda-approves-first-rsv-drug-to-protect-all-infants-from-virus-52907caf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">RSV</a> typically start spreading in the fall and peak in the winter.新冠病毒是一种较新的病毒，自几年前出现以来已经发生了很大变异，到目前为止，它经历了冬季激增和夏季高峰，就像我们今年再次看到的那样。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> One possible factor: <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sun-tired-hot-weather-heat-bb750670?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Heat waves</a> are sending people fleeing for air-conditioned indoor spaces, where Covid transmits more easily compared with outside. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/airport-travel-tips-flight-summer-a6771549?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Summer travel</a> might also play a role, as people crowd into airports and bring their germs along with them crisscrossing the world.</p><p> “We are in a very warm year and people are spending a lot of time indoors,” said Dr. Luis Ostrosky, chief of infectious diseases <strong>&nbsp;</strong> and epidemiology at UTHealth Houston and Memorial Hermann-Texas Medical Center. “People are congregating in air-conditioned settings and that is providing an opportunity for transmission.”</p><p> Covid-19 hospitalizations as of July 15 are up 10.3% from the previous week, according to CDC data.急诊科就诊次数增加了 7%，检测阳性率从 5.8% 上升至 6.3%。入院人数包括因新冠肺炎住院的患者以及因其他原因入院治疗时检测呈阳性的患者。 Deaths remain low.</p><p> Overall, Covid rates are still near historic lows, a CDC spokeswoman noted. And for most people, Covid is far less dangerous than it once was.</p><p> “Because we may start seeing seasonality patterns like we do with other respiratory diseases, I think how big this wave gets this summer will be very telling,” says Katelyn Jetelina, a scientific adviser to the CDC and White House and author of the “Your Local Epidemiologist” newsletter.</p><p> There is no new Covid strain behind current cases. A mix of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-target-xbb-strain-when-covid-shots-roll-out-this-fall-178702e1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">XBB variants</a> , which are offshoots of Omicron, play the largest role, say scientists and doctors.</p><p> Covid mutates faster than influenza, so it&#39;s changing more quickly and able to better evade people&#39;s immunity from prior infections, says Jetelina.</p><p> Covid-tracking data isn&#39;t as comprehensive as it once was. Many people aren&#39;t testing at all, and use <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/can-i-trust-my-rapid-covid-19-test-if-it-says-im-negative-11654650057?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">home rapid tests</a> if they do, which typically don&#39;t get reported to health authorities.</p><p> Since the federal government formally <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/covid-19-public-health-emergency-is-over-92ee814d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">declared the end of the pandemic</a> as a public health emergency in May, labs no longer are required to submit data on Covid-19 testing.相反，CDC 检测阳性数据来自 400 多个自愿提交数据的实验室。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824302?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Virus levels in wastewater have ticked up in the Northeast, according to one company&#39;s data.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Matias Basualdo/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Wastewater testing provides some regional clues. UTHealth Houston 和 Memorial Hermann 的 Ostrosky 表示，在休斯顿，废水处理措施在过去三周内增加了两倍。 “这始终是我们将在临床上看到的情况的先兆，”他指出。</p><p> Already, the hospital and clinic have seen roughly double the number of people testing positive for Covid-19 over the past two to three weeks, Ostrosky says.</p><p> Mariana Matus, CEO and co-founder of Biobot, a Cambridge, Mass., wastewater epidemiology company, says their data shows an 8% increase compared with the prior week in the level of the virus that causes Covid nationally. “过去几周，这种情况持续上升，”马图斯说。</p><p> In the Northeast, levels were 26% higher for the week ending July 19 compared with the previous week.她说，南方的水平高出 9%。</p><p> Overall, wastewater virus levels are still low, says Matus.去年夏天废水浓度是目前的四倍，最近几天废水浓度开始下降，这意味着浪潮可能已经达到顶峰。</p><p> Caitlin Rivers, an epidemiologist at the Johns Hopkins Center for Health Security, says Covid trend rates don&#39;t necessarily warrant changing behaviors if you&#39;re young and healthy. But elderly people and those who are immunocompromised might want to keep a closer eye on the numbers and act more cautiously, including masking in crowded indoor spaces, if they continue to rise for another month.</p><p> “It&#39;s not like we are deep in a wave,” says Rivers. “It&#39;s just heading in a direction that&#39;s making us pay closer attention.”</p><p> Write to Sumathi Reddy at <a href="mailto:Sumathi.Reddy@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Sumathi.Reddy@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/covid-19-rates-rising-summer-780ab1d7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/covid-19-rates-rising-summer-780ab1d7<author><![CDATA[Sumathi Reddy]]></author><category>摄影委托</category><category>WSJ生活工作</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>疫情/流行病</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>爆发</category><category>流行病</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Military Officers Say They Removed Niger’s President]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>华盛顿将西非国家视为对抗伊斯兰恐怖和俄罗斯在萨赫勒地区推进的堡垒<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086918"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=143CF7F1-9518-452C-91B4-B3C7091B039D&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fapparent-coup-attempt-hits-u-s-ally-niger-e3efa36d&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> A group of military officers in the West African country of Niger said Wednesday they had seized power and removed the country&#39;s elected President Mohamed Bazoum. WSJ&#39;s Gabriele Steinhauser explains the implications for the Sahel region and the US Photo: AFP/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086918"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/benoit-faucon" itemprop="url" rel="author">伯努瓦·福肯 (Benoit Faucon)</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/michael-m-phillips" itemprop="url" rel="author">迈克尔·M·菲利普斯 (Michael M. Phillips)</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 27 日凌晨 3:25（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apparent-coup-attempt-hits-u-s-ally-niger-e3efa36d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> NAIROBI, Kenya—A group of military officers in the West African country of Niger claimed that they had overthrown the elected president, shaking <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sahel-based-militants-edging-south-toward-west-africas-most-stable-and-prosperous-states-11646221800?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">one of the most-reliable US allies</a> in the fight against al Qaeda, Islamic State and Boko Haram.</p><p>周三晚间，一名尼日尔官员在国家电视台发表讲话时表示，一个名为“国家拯救祖国委员会”的组织夺取了权力，并罢免了尼日尔总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆。</p><p> “我们，国防和安全部队……已经决定结束你所知道的政权，”政变发言人阿马杜·阿卜杜拉马内上校说。 The spokesman, flanked by nine other officers, cited what he said was Niger&#39;s deteriorating security situation. He said the country&#39;s borders had been sealed and a curfew put in place, while pledging to respect human rights.</p><p> The rebellion against Bazoum, who was elected in 2021, is the latest turbulence to hit West Africa and especially the Sahel, the semiarid band just south of the Sahara where Islamist terrorists have killed thousands of civilians in recent years.</p><p> Mali, Burkina Faso and Guinea have all <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-allies-to-withdraw-forces-from-mali-11645092903?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">had elected governments removed</a> by military officers since 2020. The coups forced an end to American military training in all three countries due to legal restrictions on US military assistance.</p><p> Mali and Burkina Faso, which border Niger, have since developed closer ties with Moscow. Mali <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-guns-for-hire-fill-void-in-africa-and-elsewhere-as-western-militaries-pull-back-11640295603?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">hired mercenaries</a> from Russia&#39;s Wagner Group in 2021 and Burkina Faso earlier this year kicked out French troops that had supported its fight against encroaching violent Islamist groups.</p><p>政变领导人在尼日尔国家电视台上发表的声明表明，周三凌晨开始的叛乱已经获得了巨大的支持。据一位与总统关系密切的人士透露，心怀不满的总统卫队早些时候曾对巴祖姆发动叛乱，并包围了他的官邸。该人士表示：“这是一种不满的表达，后来升级为政变企图。”</p><p>周四上午，巴祖姆在社交媒体平台 X（前身为 Twitter）上发布的一条消息中表示，“来之不易的（民主）成果将得到维护。” In a separate post, Hassoumi Massoudou, Bazoum&#39;s foreign minister, who is traveling abroad, said he was now the government&#39;s interim chief, saying, “a coup attempt has been under way in Niger” by “factional officers.”</p><p> Army units loyal to the president were negotiating with the coup plotters outside of Bazoum&#39;s home, pressing them to surrender their weapons, the person close to the president said.总统办公室发布推文称，如果总统卫队不退缩，军队和国民警卫队“已准备好攻击他们”。</p><p> The US operates a drone base in the Nigerien town of Agadez <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-builds-new-firewall-to-stop-spread-of-militant-islamists-11670771719?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to help stem the spread of Islamist militants</a> in the Sahel.美国突击队在尼日尔全国各地的前哨基地训练尼日尔特种部队。美国军队过去常常伴随当地同行执行战斗任务，直到 2017 年伊斯兰国伏击导致四名美国士兵死亡。现在，美国人在行动中从远处为尼日尔突击队提供建议。</p><p>针对巴祖姆的武装叛乱立即引起了国际社会的谴责。</p><p> “The United States strongly condemns any effort to seize power by force and disrupt the constitutional order in Niger,” US Ambassador to the United Nations Linda Thomas-Greenfield</p>说。<p></p><p> “我们呼吁立即释放总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆。 And we call for respect for the rule of law and public safety, ” she said in a tweet Wednesday night.</p><p> Secretary of State Antony Blinken said the US was gravely concerned with developments in Niger following a call he held with Bazoum.</p><p> “我们正在密切关注尼日尔的局势和事态发展，”他于当地时间周四在新西兰惠灵顿对记者表示。 “我们谴责任何以武力夺取政权的行为。我们正在积极与尼日尔政府以及该地区和世界各地的合作伙伴进行接触，并将继续这样做，直到局势得到适当、和平的解决。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824275?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尼日尔总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆上个月在巴黎举行的一次聚会上。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卢多维奇·马林/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Blinken said the US Embassy was in the process of accounting for its personnel and family members to prepare for a potential deterioration of the situation.他说，美国与尼日尔的安全伙伴关系取决于这一局势的结果。</p><p>非洲联盟委员会主席穆萨·法基·穆罕默德指责策划者“完全背叛了共和义务”。</p><p>由 15 国组成的西非国家经济共同体发表声明称，其执行委员会“以最强烈的措辞谴责企图以武力夺取政权的行为，并呼吁政变策划者立即释放民选共和国总统，不要让健康）状况。”</p><p>尼日尔驻华盛顿大使基亚里·利曼-廷吉里 (Kiari Liman-Tinguiri) 将这次起义称为“破坏我们民主运作的企图”。他在推文中补充道：“不会向总统卫队的不诚实官员妥协。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —William Mauldin 和 Vivian Salama 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Michael M. Phillips ( <a href="mailto:Michael.Phillips@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Michael.Phillips@wsj.com)</a>和 Benoit Faucon ( <a href="mailto:benoit.faucon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">benoit.faucon@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 07:25:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/apparent-coup-attempt-hits-us-ally-niger-e3efa36d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/apparent-coup-attempt-hits-us-ally-niger-e3efa36d<author><![CDATA[Benoit FauconMichael M. Phillips]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>基亚里·利曼-廷吉里</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Russian Attack on U.S. Drone Spurs Fears of Escalation Over Syria]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>美国官员称俄罗斯本周损坏了两架美国无人机<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001088457"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824487?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周日，一架俄罗斯喷气式战斗机在叙利亚上空飞近一架美国无人机。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：美国空军/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001088457"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/michael-r-gordon" itemprop="url" rel="author">迈克尔·R·戈登</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nancy-a-youssef" itemprop="url" rel="author">南希·A·优素福</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 27 日上午 12:01 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-attack-on-u-s-drone-spurs-fears-of-escalation-over-syria-ff3b9f98"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>尽管全世界的注意力都集中在俄罗斯对乌克兰的入侵上，但俄罗斯对美国无人机的新攻击使叙利亚成为莫斯科和华盛顿之间军事竞争的一个充满争议的舞台。</p><p>周三，一架俄罗斯喷气式战斗机投下照明弹，损坏了一架飞机的机翼，凸显了冲突的风险。 <strong>&nbsp;</strong>美国官员称，美国 MQ-9“死神”无人机飞越叙利亚西北部上空。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>周三发生的事件是在周日发生的一起事件之后发生的，当时<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-jet-fighter-damages-u-s-drone-over-syria-3be72019?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">另一架 MQ-9 被损坏</a>，美国官员认为，这是俄罗斯协同努力向美军施压，要求其从叙利亚撤军。</p><p>两架美国无人机均成功返回基地。</p><p>无人机并不是最近几周俄罗斯飞行员骚扰的唯一飞机。 7月16日，一架俄罗斯战斗机如此靠近一架飞机<strong>&nbsp;</strong>美国驻中东空军最高将领亚历克苏斯·格林克维奇中将在一份声明中表示，美国涡轮螺旋桨飞机在必须飞过湍流的喷射气流时，美国机组人员面临危险。</p><p>周日事件发生后，五角大楼公开抱怨俄罗斯骚扰美国无人机的行为不专业，并发布了一段视频，展示了这场紧张的遭遇。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824491?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周日，一架美国无人机的螺旋桨受损。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：美国空军/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>在美国强调了他们周日损坏MQ-9螺旋桨的行动后，美国原本希望俄罗斯能够克制一下，但周三的新对抗却让美国人失望了。</p><p>在3月份的类似事件中，俄罗斯也没有任何悔悟的迹象，当时俄罗斯战斗机在黑海上空骚扰了一架MQ-9无人机，严重损坏了螺旋桨，美国被迫将其坠入下面的水域。俄罗斯国防部表示，在此事件中，俄罗斯国防部长谢尔盖·绍伊古向涉案的两名飞行员颁发了奖项。 <strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p>周三，一名俄罗斯军方官员将责任归咎于美国，称美国无人机对两架俄罗斯飞机进行了“危险接近”，促使飞机通过释放照明弹进行防御性反应。 “美国继续向国际社会误导”，奥列格·古里诺夫少将</p>说。<p></p><p>退休。 2019年至2022年负责美国在中东军事行动的美国中央司令部司令、海军陆战队上将弗兰克·麦肯齐表示，莫斯科的战略是在美国军事足迹遍布叙利亚之际，试图从叙利亚撤回美军。中东是非常温和的。</p><p>麦肯齐说，“他们想让游戏变得太丰富，让我们无法玩，这样我们就会退出而不是坚持我们的立场”。 “俄罗斯人倾向于通过升级来缓和局势。”</p><p>莫斯科的行动促使美国官员考虑如果俄罗斯成功击落一架美国无人机，如何应对，包括通过非军事手段。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=3912093C-EDC6-4EDE-806D-57C558C8E8DB&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Frussian-attack-on-u-s-drone-spurs-fears-of-escalation-over-syria-ff3b9f98&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">自乌克兰反攻开始以来，乌克兰大量使用廉价第一人称视角无人机对俄罗斯坦克和大型武器进行神风特攻队式攻击。图片插图：杰里米·舒巴克<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“这当然是我们更加关注的事情，”一名国防官员表示。</p><p>美国军方周三表示，十几架先进的F-35战斗机已抵达中东，其任务是阻止伊朗对霍尔木兹海峡航运的袭击。但是<strong>&nbsp;</strong>美国军方还在声明中指出，这些飞机“如果需要，可以在整个战区的有争议空域飞行”，指的是美国正在进行的击败伊斯兰国的任务。</p><p>自2015年俄罗斯军队部署支持叙利亚总统巴沙尔·阿萨德以来，叙利亚两军之间一直存在紧张局势</p>在他对对手的残酷竞选中。<p></p><p>美国在叙利亚仍有约 900 名士兵，协助当地合作伙伴库尔德人领导的叙利亚民主力量打击伊斯兰国残余势力。但这些美军正在东部行动，远离疑似伊斯兰国和基地组织领导人活动的西北飞地。</p><p>美国此前曾在叙利亚西北部使用过无人机，多年来，两军一直通过将俄罗斯驻叙利亚指挥官与美国驻该地区指挥官联系起来的冲突消除渠道，成功避免了直接冲突。</p><p> 11月，俄罗斯向叙利亚上空的一架无人机发射了一枚地对空导弹，但未能击落飞机。据美国军方官员称，本月早些时候， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-jets-confront-u-s-drones-over-syria-b74be68a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">俄罗斯飞机连续几天骚扰美国 MQ-9 飞机</a>，并驾驶一架 An-30 侦察机飞越叙利亚东南部的美国前哨基地。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="428" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824497?width=700&amp;height=428" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美国军方周三表示，十几架先进的 F-35 喷气式战斗机已抵达中东，以阻止伊朗对霍尔木兹海峡航运的袭击。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：鲍里斯·罗斯勒/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>有几个因素导致紧张局势加剧。首先，两军陷入任务冲突，美军试图追击伊斯兰国残余分子，该组织的领导人隐藏在叙利亚西北部，俄罗斯飞机一直在该地区活动，但远离叙利亚东部，美军一直在那里与当地盟友合作。</p><p>另一个因素是，由于美国缩减了在该地区的军事足迹，该地区的力量平衡发生了变化。美国派F-22战机飞越叙利亚的日子已经一去不复返了，美国只有更少的战机来试图反击驻扎在叙利亚的俄罗斯飞机。</p><p>美国官员表示，另一个因素是俄罗斯军队在叙利亚日益咄咄逼人的姿态。周日击落一架美国无人机的俄罗斯战斗机上涂有“Z”符号，俄罗斯部队在入侵乌克兰时曾使用过该符号。</p><p>卡内基国际和平基金会的安德鲁·韦斯表示：“俄罗斯人想要进行恐吓，破坏美国不会受到挑战的感觉。” “美国在保护地面和空中人民的同时，试图不上钩。”</p><p>写信给 Michael R. Gordon（ <a href="mailto:michael.gordon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">michael.gordon@wsj.com</a> ）和 Nancy A. Youssef（ <a href="mailto:nancy.youssef@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">nancy.youssef@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ Russian-attack-on-us-drone-spurs-fears-of-escalation-over-syria-ff3b9f98</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ Russian-attack-on-us-drone-spurs-fears-of-escalation-over-syria-ff3b9f98<author><![CDATA[Michael R. GordonNancy A. Youssef]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Hunter Biden Pleads Not Guilty to Tax Charges]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>法官推迟在法庭听证会上考虑认罪协议<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086059"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=0B3DB0F9-BB08-44C5-9D27-7C99347D4C8F&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fhunter-biden-plea-deal-in-jeopardy-ff556d70&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">照片：安娜·钱梅梅克/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086059"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sadie-gurman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sadie Gurman</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/aruna-viswanatha" itemprop="url" rel="author">Aruna Viswanatha</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 26 日下午 5:21（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-plea-deal-in-jeopardy-ff556d70"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>特拉华州威尔明顿——周三，亨特·拜登对税务指控表示不认罪，在法官表示亨特·拜登尚未准备好接受<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-guilty-plea-federal-court-3b15f98b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">他与检察官达成的认罪协议</a>后，情况发生了惊人的逆转。</p><p>在一场持续三个小时的激烈听证会上，拜登总统之子的一名律师最初与检察官就未来指控的可能性发生争执。在双方澄清<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-bidens-messy-path-to-a-plea-deal-c22bd962?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">协议</a>后，美国地区法官玛丽莲·诺雷卡表示，她需要更多信息才能决定是否签署协议。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “这些协议并不简单，它们包含非典型条款，”她说，并补充道：“我无法决定接受或拒绝认罪协议，我需要推迟它。”</p><p>被前总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>任命为法官的诺雷卡法官的最后一刻的剧变，标志着司法部对亨特·拜登的财务、商业交易以及有据可查的毒瘾和酗酒成瘾的曲折且具有政治爆炸性的调查的最新转折。</p><p>几周前公开的认罪协议大纲使亨特·拜登有可能将法律麻烦抛在脑后，尽管国会山的共和党人已经升级了对他涉嫌不当行为的听证会和指控，并试图将其与拜登总统联系起来。发起<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-touts-job-growth-in-first-re-election-campaign-rally-9337f3c2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">连任竞选</a>。</p><p>检察官保留了未来对亨特·拜登提出指控的可能性，包括与司法部长期以来一直在审查的外国游说法有关的指控。周三的结果意味着他的法律困境仍然存在，并且随着 2024 年竞选活动的推进，可能会为众议院和参议院的共和党人提供新的素材。</p><p>众议院议长凯文·麦卡锡（加利福尼亚州共和党）表示，众议院可能会对拜登总统进行弹劾调查，理由是亨特·拜登的海外商业交易涉及腐败。</p><p>白宫一直表示，拜登总统没有与他的儿子讨论亨特·拜登的商业往来，也没有参与其中。参议院多数党领袖查克·舒默（纽约州民主党人）表示：“我对检方有信心……任何人都不应在政治、意识形态上干涉此事，让正义得以伸张。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824383?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">亨特·拜登在特拉华州威尔明顿举行认罪听证会后离开联邦法院。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔纳森·恩斯特/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>如果负责此案的法官最终不宽恕认罪协议，亨特·拜登将面临目前针对他的指控的审判，就像共和党 2024 年总统候选人领先者特朗普面临司法部<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indicted-in-document-case-b4e563d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">指控他处理机密信息不当一样</a>。预计特朗普还将因涉嫌破坏 2020 年大选而被起诉。特朗普否认有任何不当行为。</p><p>小拜登原本预计会承认<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-charged-with-tax-crimes-bd2dea0a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">轻罪税务指控</a>，并已达成协议以避免枪支指控。共和党人指责司法部给予拜登一项宽松的协议，这是其他处于类似情况下的人永远不会得到的。该部门否认有任何偏袒。</p><p>在听证会上，亨特·拜登和他的律师坐在一起，静静地看着诉讼程序展开。他透露了自己的康复情况，并告诉法官，在过去的二十年里，他因吸毒和酗酒至少接受了六次治疗。他说，他最后一次吸毒或酗酒是在 2019 年 6 月。</p><p>白宫新闻秘书卡琳·让-皮埃尔周三下午对记者说：“亨特·拜登是一名普通公民，这对他来说是个人问题。” “正如我们所说，总统和第一夫人，他们爱他们的儿子，并将继续支持他重建生活。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824384?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">执法人员保护了特拉华州威尔明顿联邦法院周围地区的安全。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔纳森·恩斯特/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这场骚乱始于周三，当时检察官利奥·怀斯坚称对亨特·拜登活动的调查仍在进行中，并在回答法官的问题时表示，他可能面临更多的外国游说指控。</p><p>对此，亨特·拜登的律师克里斯·克拉克表示，他不同意这种解释，并认为该协议排除了额外指控的可能性，并随后补充道：“就我而言，认罪协议是无效的。”</p><p>休会后，亨特·拜登的法律团队表示，该协议涵盖了他在 2014 年至 2019 年期间与税务犯罪相关的责任，并涵盖了毒品和枪支犯罪。法官问亨特·拜登是否曾承诺提供任何其他保护措施来诱使他认罪，他说：“没有，法官大人。”</p><p>然后，法官就协议的两个方面中包含的条款向双方施压，包括为什么税收协议是根据一项取消法院审查能力的法规提出的，而枪支协议则要求法院决定亨特·拜登是否拥有违反了协议。诺雷卡法官表示，这可能会让她不恰当地做出通常由检察官做出的决定。</p><p> “我对这项规定的合宪性感到担忧，所以我对这项协议的合宪性感到担忧，”她说。</p><p>法官给了双方 30 天的时间来澄清她的角色并提供更多信息。届时，亨特·拜登可以认罪并将他谈判达成的协议正式化。</p><p>亨特·拜登在听证会结束后走出法院走向一辆等候的SUV时没有发表任何评论。</p><p>周二，众议院筹款委员会共和党主席、众议员贾森·史密斯（密苏里州共和党）就此案提交了一份不同寻常的简报，敦促法院考虑拒绝认罪协议。它强调了他的小组最近从两名国税局调查员那里听到的证词，称政治考虑可能影响了调查。简报称：“为了所有公民的完全透明和公平，法院掌握这些信息至关重要。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824385?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">共和党众议员贾森·史密斯就亨特·拜登案提交了一份简报，敦促法院考虑拒绝认罪协议。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Rod Lamkey/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>诺雷卡法官表示，她没有时间全面审查这份冗长的申请。</p><p>与联邦检察官达成的协议本应标志着特拉华州美国检察官大卫·韦斯长达一年的调查的高潮，韦斯由特朗普任命，在拜登政府期间一直留任，以彻查对总统儿子的刑事调查。作为协议的一部分，检察官同意，只要亨特·拜登保持不吸毒并同意不再拥有枪支，就不会对持有枪支提起单独的重罪指控。</p><p>共和党人承诺继续推进<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-tries-to-end-legal-woes-as-republicans-vow-to-keep-probing-4b6ac7e9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">自己的调查</a>，旨在通过拜登总统的儿子来污蔑他，并在 2024 年选举周期升温之际让他的麻烦成为焦点。</p><p>众议院监督委员会主席詹姆斯·科默（肯塔基州共和党人）周三表示：“我们将继续追踪拜登父子的资金轨迹。”他赞扬法官“拒绝对这一“甜心交易”盖章。</p><p>民主党人将共和党领导的调查视为政治表演，监督委员会高级成员众议员杰米·拉斯金（马里兰州民主党人）称其为“检查员克鲁索式的对不存在事物的探索”。</p><p>韦斯的办公室同意建议仅缓刑，作为亨特·拜登认罪协议的一部分，但法官拥有最终决定权。亨特·拜登每项罪名最高可被判处 12 个月监禁和 10 万美元罚款。如果亨特·拜登未能兑现不拥有枪支和不吸毒的承诺，枪支指控最高可判处 10 年监禁和巨额罚款。</p><p>该调查于 2018 年开始，首先审查了小拜登的海外商业交易，但近年来，调查重点转向了他的纳税情况以及他在购买枪支表格上的虚假声明，即他没有使用毒品或吸毒成瘾。亨特·拜登在 2021 年的回忆录《美丽的事物》中详细描述了他长期吸毒的情况，并写道，他在 2018 年“每 15 分钟”就抽一根可卡因。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您认为此案最有趣的是什么？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>韦斯表示，亨特·拜登在2017年和2018年的年收入都超过150万美元，尽管每年欠税超过10万美元，但他没有为此纳税。 《华尔街日报》此前报道称<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/prosecutors-advance-tax-probe-of-hunter-biden-11648465200?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，他偿还了约 100 万美元</a>，而指控称他未能按时支付至少 20 万美元。在检方预计提供更多细节之前，尚不清楚造成这种明显差异的原因。</p><p>根据与枪支指控相关的法庭文件，亨特·拜登在 2018 年 10 月拥有一把柯尔特眼镜蛇 38SPL 左轮手枪，尽管他吸毒成瘾并被禁止拥有枪支。</p><p>这项调查历经两届政府历时五年，并面临许多挑战，包括调查人员之间对如何进行的分歧。到 2022 年中期，调查人员认为有足够的证据来指控亨特·拜登，但<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-case-decision-paused-amid-discussions-between-defense-lawyers-and-prosecutors-11665094544?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">检察官在审查辩方证据时推迟了数月</a>。除其他问题外，检察官还纠结于他的毒瘾是否可以为潜在的刑事税务案件提供有效的辩护。</p><p>拜登总统任命司法部长梅里克·加兰（Merrick Garland）的部分原因是他承诺让该部门的调查不受政治影响。他捍卫了调查的独立性，韦斯表示，他被赋予了广泛的自由度，可以在他认为合适的情况下追查此案。</p><p>周一，司法部表示韦斯将在众议院司法委员会作证，并提供了 9 月和 10 月的可能日期，强调他应该在公开听证会上发言，而不是共和党寻求的闭门听证会。</p><p>写信给 Sadie Gurman <a href="mailto:sadie.gurman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(sadie.gurman@wsj.com)</a>和 Aruna Viswanatha ( <a href="mailto:aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com</a> )</p><p id="correction" class="correction"><strong>更正和放大</strong><br>亨特·拜登每项罪名最高可被判处 12 个月监禁和 10 万美元罚款。本文的早期版本错误地表示，拜登每项罪名均面临 25,000 美元的罚款。 （7月26日更正）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 21:21:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-plea-deal-in-jeopardy-ff556d70</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-plea-deal-in-jeopardy-ff556d70<author><![CDATA[Sadie GurmanAruna Viswanatha]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>税务欺诈</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>玛丽莲·诺瑞卡</category><category>凯文·麦卡锡</category><category>查克·舒默</category><category>詹姆斯·科默</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>税务欺诈</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Federal Reserve Raises Interest Rates to 22-Year High]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>官员们放慢了今年的增长步伐，但不确定他们是否已完全解决通货膨胀问题<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086188"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=7E0252B4-152F-44EE-9C61-910343546CB6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ffederal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">观看美联储主席杰罗姆·鲍威尔的新闻发布会。<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086188"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nick-timiraos" itemprop="url" rel="author">Nick Timiraos</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 26 日下午 4:04（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>华盛顿——美联储周三恢复加息，加息幅度为 25 个百分点，这将使利率升至<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/fed-meeting-interest-rate-decision-today-july-2023?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">22 年来的最高点</a>。</p><p>由于官员们争论是否采取了足够的措施来对抗通胀，上个月一致决定将基准联邦基金利率提高至 5.25% 至 5.5% 的区间，结束了加息<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fed-holds-rates-steady-but-expects-more-increases-b1be87f2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的短暂停顿</a>。这是自 2022 年 3 月以来第 11 次加息，当时利率从接近于零的水平上调。</p><p>美联储<a href="https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/files/monetary20230726a1.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">对其会后声明</a>进行了最小程度的修改，没有就其未来的政策计划提供新的指导。</p><p>在会后的新闻发布会上，美联储主席杰罗姆·鲍威尔不排除在央行下次会议上再次加息的可能性，但他强调了央行已经做了多少工作，以及货币政策需要多长时间才能恢复正常。通胀降温。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>更多关于美联储的信息</h4><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/files/monetary20230726a1.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">美联储货币政策声明</a></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/fed-meeting-interest-rate-decision-today-july-2023?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">决策后股市动摇</a></li></ul></div></div><p>他说：“当我们让这一切展开时，我们可以保持一点耐心，同时也保持坚决的态度。” “我们认为，当然，我们需要在一段时间内将政策维持在限制性水平，如果我们认为合适，我们将准备进一步加息。”</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/fed-meeting-interest-rate-decision-today-july-2023" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener"><br></a>美联储决定后， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/fed-meeting-interest-rate-decision-today-july-2023" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">市场涨跌互现</a>。</p><p>经济增长可能过于强劲，鲍威尔<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/markets-appear-convinced-the-fed-can-pull-off-a-soft-landing-700a40dd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">无法像许多投资者预期的那样</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/investors-can-read-the-feds-poker-face-a1934d25?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">暗示周三的加息将是当前紧缩周期的最后一次</a>。与此同时，近期通胀放缓可能会减轻央行官员继续加息的压力。</p><p>在六月份的上一次会议上，官员们维持利率稳定，但预计今年还会加息两次。美联储官员计划今年再召开三次会议，下一次会议将于 9 月举行。</p><p>通货膨胀已从去年夏天创下的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-inflation-june-2022-consumer-price-index-11657664129" target="_blank" class="icon none">40 年来的高</a>点回落，6 月份消费者价格指数同比上涨 3%。这远低于 2022 年 6 月 9.1% 的峰值，当时汽油价格达到<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gasoline-prices-reach-5-a-gallon-nationwide-for-the-first-time-11654910506" target="_blank" class="icon none">每加仑 5 美元的创纪录平均水平。</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=DE0B91C0-D4B9-4619-AFE8-7EA4E62BC84B&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ffederal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">美联储是当今美国经济的核心，但其权力是几十年来积累的。它的决定可以降低通货膨胀或引发经济衰退。 《华尔街日报》解释了美联储的成立方式及其所扮演的角色。插图：赵安妮<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>美联储官员一直担心，潜在的价格压力可能会更加持久，因为紧张的劳动力市场允许工人讨价还价以获得更高的工资， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/last-mile-of-the-inflation-fight-will-be-the-hardest-86bcebb1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">从而使通胀进一步下降变得更加困难</a>。</p><p>不包括波动较大的食品和能源类别的核心价格在 6 月份 CPI 中录得两年多以来的最小月度涨幅。尽管如此，6 月份核心 CPI 仍较去年同期上涨 4.8%。直到去年，核心消费者物价指数(CPI)自20世纪90年代初以来还没有出现过这样的涨幅。</p><p>美联储官员关注核心通胀，因为他们认为核心通胀比总体通胀率更能预测未来通胀。</p><p>美联储力求将通货膨胀率长期保持在 2%，这是通过其首选指标——个人消费支出价格指数来衡量的。美联储通过加息减缓经济增长来对抗通货膨胀，这会导致金融状况收紧，例如借贷成本上升、股价下跌和美元走强。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824356?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>美联储在2022年大幅加息，然后在年底放慢了步伐。六月保持利率稳定提供了一种进一步放慢加息步伐并研究这些快速变动的影响的方法，特别是在担忧之后<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-05-08-2023/card/banking-stress-a-top-risk-to-u-s-economy-fed-survey-says-tan3K36YS98VljIazfHP?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">&nbsp;</a> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/jerome-powell-says-bank-failures-underscore-need-for-stronger-regulation-supervision-8f386569?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">鲍威尔上个月表示</a>，今年春季的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-05-08-2023/card/banking-stress-a-top-risk-to-u-s-economy-fed-survey-says-tan3K36YS98VljIazfHP?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">银行业压力</a>可能会进一步限制信贷。</p><p>近几个月来，官员们曾就继续加息的速度表示分歧。根据联邦公开市场委员会的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fed-officials-supported-raising-rates-after-june-pause-7b525544?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一份书面报告</a>，虽然制定政策的联邦公开市场委员会的所有 11 名投票成员都同意上个月保持利率稳定的决定，但 18 名投票和无投票权官员中的一些人会支持在 6 月会议上加息。本月早些时候发布的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fed-officials-supported-raising-rates-after-june-pause-7b525544?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">会议</a>。</p><p>美联储官员每年举行八次会议，或者大约每个季度举行两次会议。尽管鲍威尔上个月表示，他不排除在连续政策会议上加息的可能性，但他表示，如果经济发展符合当前预期，预计每季度加息的速度可能会放缓。</p><p>然而，少数美联储官员表示，他们可能更愿意在央行 9 月份的会议上再次加息。</p><p>美联储官员在六月份提高了利率预测，部分原因是他们预计通胀方面的进展将会放缓。如果通胀继续降温，这一事态发展将引发人们对是否需要在今年晚些时候再次加息的疑问。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您认为美联储下一步应该如何行动？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>认为美联储加息影响尚未完全显现的官员更有可能倾向于等到11月或12月再决定是否适合进行第二次加息。</p><p>如果届时经济活动进一步放缓，官员们可能会决定不再加息，并进入紧缩行动的新阶段——在通胀放缓的情况下保持利率稳定。这将导致通胀调整后的实际利率上升。</p><p> “对于紧缩周期的最后一部分，随着时间的推移延长它是有意义的。他们正在微调。他们不知道确切的目的地。对冲基金公司 Citadel 全球固定收益经济研究主管 Angel Ubide 表示，慢慢来是有意义的。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823209?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美联储主席杰罗姆·鲍威尔不排除在央行下次会议上再次加息的可能性。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：德鲁·安格勒/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>能源和大宗商品价格是过去一年通胀<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-global-energy-shock-price-collapse-provides-unexpected-economic-boon-8c2b6660?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">下降的</a>主要原因。 2007 年至 2021 年担任波士顿联储主席的埃里克·罗森格伦 (Eric Rosengren) 表示，最近其中一些价格的上涨可能突显了为什么官员们在假设通胀进一步下降时要保持谨慎。</p><p>如果官员们有理由认为这种改善将是短暂的——例如，因为工资增长保持坚挺，那么未来几个月核心通胀的放缓可能会给美联储带来一个新的难题。 “这就是老话，‘小心你的愿望’，”2018 年至 2022 年 1 月期间担任鲍威尔副手的理查德·克拉里达 (Richard Clarida) 说。<br><br>过去一年，经济学家们一直在争论劳动力需求放缓是否会导致失业率上升，或者企业是否会减少职位空缺但不减少员工数量，从而导致失业率上升。</p><p> “很多关于劳动力市场的争论都不是重点，”克拉里达说。 “如果我还在那里，我会担心的是：如果我们的工资不减速，生产力不提高，那么我们就不会达到通胀目标。 ”</p><p> Write to Nick Timiraos at <a href="mailto:Nick.Timiraos@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Nick.Timiraos@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 20:04:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c<author><![CDATA[Nick Timiraos]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>华尔街日报华盛顿</category><category>inflation</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>Inflation Figures/Price Indices</category><category> Monetary Policy</category><category> Interest Rates</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>Inflation</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>杰罗姆·鲍威尔</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>inflation figures</category><category> price indices</category><category> monetary policy</category><category> interest rates</category><category>经济新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[UFOs Are a Common Sight, Former Military Official Tells Congress]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Lawmakers push for more transparency on the phenomena <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001083955"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=82BCA119-BD58-457A-84DC-03BE0735FECF&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fhouse-oversight-committee-congress-ufo-hearing-ceeceae6&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> A panel of experts testified to Congress on Wednesday about the potential threats that unidentified aerial phenomena pose to national security. Photo: Elizabeth Frantz/Reuters<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001083955"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/joseph-deavila" itemprop="url" rel="author">Joseph De Avila</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 26, 2023 3:43 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-oversight-committee-congress-ufo-hearing-ceeceae6"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Former military and intelligence officials <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KQ7Dw-739VY" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">testified to a congressional panel</a> Wednesday that they have seen UFOs and said they could pose risks to national security.</p><p> The former officials called for the US government to share what it knows about the phenomena.</p><p> Two of the witnesses, former US Navy fighter pilots, said they have seen “unidentified anomalous phenomena,” or UAP, a phrase the federal government uses to refer to what are commonly known as UFOs.</p><p> One of the pilots testified that encounters with UAP are common among military aircrews and commercial pilots.</p><p> A former intelligence official also testified at the hearing that he believes the US government has hidden from the public that it possesses aircraft of a nonhuman origin.</p><p> Wednesday&#39;s hearing, by a House Oversight subcommittee, is Congress&#39;s latest push for transparency around UAP, which have long fascinated the public. The federal government has begun disclosing some information about UAP. It has set up task forces to investigate the phenomena and plans to release more findings. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824168?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ryan Graves, David Grusch and David Fravor testify before a congressional panel Wednesday.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: jim lo scalzo/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “The lack of transparency regarding UAPs has fueled wild speculation and debate for decades, eroding public trust in the very institutions that are meant to serve and protect them,” said Rep. Glenn Grothman, (R., Wis.). “There lies a pressing demand for government transparency and accountability that cannot be overlooked, and that&#39;s been a problem that&#39;s been around for 50 years.”</p><p> Witness David Grusch, a former member of a US Air Force panel on UAP, has said the federal government has withheld information about the recoveries of aircraft of nonhuman origin from Congress and the public.</p><p> Grusch told lawmakers Wednesday that during the course of his work with a UAP task force, he was informed of a UAP crash-retrieval and reverse-engineering program that had existed for decades. When he tried to learn more about that program, he was denied access, he said. He reported what he learned to his superiors and to multiple inspectors general, he said.</p><p> Grusch said he believes the US government is in possession of UAP based on interviewing 40 witnesses over four years with direct knowledge of the program.</p><p> He testified that the US government has recovered nonhuman biologic material from crashed UAP, citing people with direct knowledge of the program.</p><p> Grusch declined to elaborate on many of his answers, saying it would pertain to classified information that he was barred from discussing in a public hearing.</p><p> The Pentagon&#39;s UAP task force, the All-domain Anomaly Resolution Office, hasn&#39;t been able to substantiate claims that any federal programs have possessed or reverse-engineered extraterrestrial materials, a spokesperson for the Defense Department said.</p><p> “The Department is fully committed to openness and accountability to the American people, which it must balance with its obligation to protect sensitive information, sources, and methods,” the spokesperson said.</p><p> The All-domain Anomaly Resolution Office has also said it has found no credible evidence of extraterrestrial activity.</p><p> Rep. Tim Burchett (R., Tenn.), and Rep.</p> Anna Paulina Luna (R., Fla.), said after the meeting they would seek a closed-door hearing with Grusch.<p></p><p> The committee plans to hold further public hearings on UAP, Burchett said.</p><p> “We&#39;re going to start talking to people, we&#39;re going to start naming names,” Burchett said.</p><p> The other two witnesses are former US Navy fighter pilots Ryan Graves, executive director of the UAP-focused advocacy group Americans for Safe Aerospace, and retired Cmdr. David Fravor.</p><p> “These sightings are not rare or isolated,” said Graves, who served in the Navy for over a decade. “Military aircrews and commercial pilots, trained observers whose lives depend on accurate identification, are frequently witnessing these phenomena.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=6E9B0F13-BE4D-4329-97BE-08CE3251BA6A&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fhouse-oversight-committee-congress-ufo-hearing-ceeceae6&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Video shared by NASA in late May during a meeting on UFOs shows an unidentified spherical object flying. Military officials said they have been unable to explain what the object is. Photo: NASA TV<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Graves said his aircrew saw UAP during a training exercise off the coast of Virginia Beach, Va. Two jets encountered “a dark gray or black cube inside of a clear sphere” and the object came within 50 feet of the lead aircraft, he said. It was estimated to be 5 to 15 feet in diameter, he said.</p><p> The mission was terminated, Graves said. The squadron submitted a safety report, but there was no official acknowledgment of the incident, he said.</p><p> The encounters with UAP became so common that the aircrew would discuss the risk of the objects during preflight briefings, Graves said.</p><p> Fravor&#39;s testimony included his account of witnessing UAP in 2004 off the coast of San Diego. Fravor had been directed to inspect an object, and was told by the mission&#39;s air controller that these objects had been observed for over two weeks coming down from over 80,000 feet and rapidly descending down to 20,000 feet, hanging there for hours and then going straight back up.</p><p> Fravor said he saw a small white object that looked like a Tic Tac and had no rotors or wings. It was “moving very abruptly over the white water, like a ping-pong ball,” he said.</p><p> Fravor flew his aircraft closer to get a better view of the UAP, and “it rapidly accelerated and disappeared,” he said.</p><p> The air controller informed him that the object was now about 60 miles away, traveling that distance in less than a minute, Fravor said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823575?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Wednesday&#39;s hearing is Congress&#39;s latest push for transparency around &#39;unidentified anomalous phenomena,&#39; or UAP.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: US DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE/HANDOUT/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Fravor said he believed UAP posed a potential threat to national security, especially if a foreign adversary captures one and is able to duplicate the technology.</p><p> “The technology we faced was far superior to anything that we had,” said Fravor, referring to the UAP he witnessed in 2004.</p><p> All three witnesses said the UAP may be probing for weakness in the US military system.</p><p> Provisions in the Senate&#39;s version of this year&#39;s National Defense Authorization Act would require federal agencies to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rumors-flying-around-about-ufos-prompt-push-for-release-of-files-6477de49" target="_blank" class="icon none">hand over records related to UAP</a> to a panel with the power to declassify them. The provisions have bipartisan support.</p><p> Federal officials have begun releasing some information about UAP. The Office of the Director of National Intelligence released a report in 2021 that reviewed <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ufo-report-cites-unidentified-aerial-phenomena-that-defy-worldly-explanation-u-s-official-says-11624653953?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">dozens of reports of mysterious flying objects</a> between 2004 and 2021. The report found several examples of objects that lacked visible forms of propulsion or that appeared to use technology beyond the known capabilities of the US or its adversaries.</p><p> US defense officials released videos of such objects last year during the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ufos-are-potential-national-security-threat-congressman-warns-at-hearing-11652797199?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">first Congressional hearing</a> on the subject in more than half a century. One video, taken from the cockpit of an aircraft, showed a spherical object flying to the right of the aircraft. Military officials were unable to explain what the object was.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What do you think explains UFOs?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Sean Kirkpatrick, director of the All-domain Anomaly Resolution Office, said in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nasas-ufo-research-team-to-brief-the-public-cd537b3f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">public testimony in May</a> his office is studying about 800 cases of UAP reported from 1996 to 2023. Only a small percentage of those cases are anomalies that can&#39;t be explained, he said.</p><p> The National Aeronautics and Space Administration has <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nasa-is-building-a-team-to-study-ufos-11654805273?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">established a separate panel</a> tasked with reviewing nonclassified data on UAP. The team plans to issue a report on its findings this summer.</p><p> <em>—Isaac Yu contributed to this article.</em></p><p> Write to Joseph De Avila at <a href="mailto:joseph.deavila@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">joseph.deavila@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 19:43:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-oversight-committee-congress-ufo-hearing-ceeceae6</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-oversight-committee-congress-ufo-hearing-ceeceae6<author><![CDATA[Joseph De Avila]]></author><category> WSJSpeeddesk</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> David Fravor</category><category> David Grusch</category><category> Ryan Graves</category><category> Sean Kirkpatrick</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category></item></channel></rss>